  "notes": "Ligurian (Zeneise / Zenéize), reference variety Genoese (Zenéize). Gallo-Italic language of Liguria, ~500,000 speakers. INPUT CONTRACT: this spec expects text in the standardised grafia ofiçiâ of the Académia Ligùstica do Brénno (the orthography of the Ligurian Wikipedia and of Toso's dictionaries); raw or ad-hoc spellings are out of scope. Modelled hallmark features of the grafia ofiçiâ: (1) o=/u/ (Genoese o is Italian u; ó also /u/, ô /uː/), while ò=/ɔ/, ö=/ɔː/. (2) u=/y/ (front rounded), û/ü=/yː/. (3) x=/ʒ/ — the diagnostic Genoese grapheme, the French j sound. (4) eu=/ø/ (êu /øː/). (5) æ=/ɛː/ (çitæ 'city'). (6) ç=/s/. (7) z=/z/ always (NOT an affricate). (8) sc=/ʃ/ before a front vowel (else /sk/), and the trigraph scc=/ʃtʃ/. (9) the velar nasal /ŋ/, written n-/nn- intervocalically and realised word-finally, with nasalisation of the preceding vowel (allophone_rules). (10) circumflex/diaeresis encode phonemic vowel length; the grafia marks stress with the written accent. Degemination is total in modern Genoese, so double consonants map to a single phoneme. Historical lingua franca of Mediterranean maritime trade (Forner 1975).",
